<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-201-110  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 201 110.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Learning  April 1989 v8 n6 p6(4).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Technology in Soviet schools: up close and personal. (part one ofa two-part series)</TITLE><AUTHOR>Resta, Paul E.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The 'Computers in US Education' seminar traveled to eight Sovietcities within a 20-month period.andP;  The three-day seminar was partof a US Information Agency (USIA) multi-media exhibit illustratingthe US's communications and information revolution.andP;  The SovietSchool Project is part of a major effort to transform Sovietschools through the use of microcomputers.andP;  Significant use ofmicrocomputers began in 1985 with the introduction of 'ThePrinciples of Informatics and Computer Technology' as a compulsorysubject in the 9th and 10th grade curriculum.andP;  The goals of theInformatics course are to provide all secondary students with somecomputer training, provide advanced pre-professional training tointerested students, and to familiarize teachers with the use ofmicrocomputers.andP;  The Moscow-New York educationaltelecommunications project is a pilot program that links 10 Moscowschools with 10 New York schools.andP;  The aim of the project is touse telecommunications as a learning tool and a means ofstrengthening cross-cultural understanding.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Soviet UnionEducationComputersComputer-Assisted InstructionSeminarsSecondary Schools.andO;Feature:   illustrationphotograph.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>